Analyzing the melanoma data with pseudo-observation approaches

In the following, we apply the proposed method to a melanoma data from the Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group phase III clinical trial e1684 (Kirkwood et al. 1996). We illustrated both the mixture cure (MC) and bounded cumulative hazard (BCH) models.

The Melanoma data

Data preparation

The dataset is available from the R package smcure (Cai et al. 2012):

> data(e1684, package = "smcure")
> head(e1684)
  TRT FAILTIME FAILCENS         AGE SEX
1   1  1.15068        1 -11.0359437   0
2   1  0.62466        1  -5.1290437   0
3   0  1.89863        0  23.1859563   1
4   0  0.45479        1  11.1448563   1
5   0  2.09041        1 -13.3208437   0
6   1  9.38356        0   0.9421563   0

The e1684 data is a data.frame that contains 284 patients and the five variables. The five variables are:

  • TRT Treatment indicator; 1 = IFN treatment, 0 = control group
  • FAILTIME Observed relapse-free time; 1 = event
  • FAILCENS Censoring indicator, 1 = relapse of melanoma happens, 0 = censoring
  • AGE Patients’ age, centered to the mean
  • SEX Patients’ gender; 1 = female, 0 = male

The event of interest is the relapse of melanoma and the primary objective is to determine whether the high dose interferon alpha-2b (IFN) regimen in postoperative adjuvant therapy would lead to a significantly prolonged interval of relapse-free for melanoma.

We remove missing values from the original dataset.

> e1684 <- na.omit(e1684)

Checking for cure

The following figure shows the Kaplan-Meier (KM) estimate stratified by TRT and SEX.

> library(survival)
> library(survminer)
> ggsurvplot(survfit(Surv(FAILTIME, FAILCENS) ~ TRT + SEX, data = e1684),
+            legend.title = "", 
+            legend.labs = c("Control/Male", "Control/Female", "Treatment/Male", "Treatment/Female")) +  
+   labs(title = "The melanoma data")

The KM estimates level off at the end, suggesting a fraction of nonsusceptibility to the recurrence of melanoma. This observation is confirmed by the Maller-Zhou test with a \(p\)-value of \(< 0.001\).

> npcure::testmz(FAILTIME, FAILCENS, e1684)
Maller-Zhou test 

 statistic   n      p.value
        31 284 5.543952e-15

Notations and models

Notations

We define the following notations.

  • \(Y\): cure status of a subject;
    • \(Y = 1\) if the subject eventually experiences an event (uncured, susceptible)
    • \(Y = 0\) if the subject is a survivor (cured, non-susceptible).
  • \(T\): survival time;
    • \(T=YT^{*}+(1-Y)\times\infty\)where \(T^{*}<\infty\) is the failure time if the subject is susceptible.
  • \(\tilde T\): observed survival time;
    • \(\tilde{T}=\min\{T,C \}\), where \(C\) is the censoring time.
  • \(\delta\): censoring indicator;
    • \(\delta = 1\), the subject experienced an event. This implies \(Y=1\).
    • \(\delta = 0\), the subject was censored. The cure status \(Y\) is not observed.
  • \(X\) and \(Z\) are vectors of covariates with dimensions \(p\) and \(q\), respectively.

Mixture cure model

The MC model expresses the population survival function as \[\begin{equation} \label{mixture} S(t)=(1-\pi)+\pi S_{u}(t), \end{equation}\] where \(\pi=P(Y=1)\) is the uncured rate and \(S_{u}(t)\) is the conditional survival function of \(T^*\) given \(Y=1\). The two components, incidence and latency, are modeled by the logistic regression model and the Cox proportional hazards model, respectively. We term this the PHMC model.

Bounded cumulative hazard model

Suppose \(\Lambda(t)\) is the cumulative hazard function of \(T^*\) such that \(\Lambda(\infty)=\theta>0\). Under the BCH model, the population survival function can be written as \[\begin{equation*}\label{NonMC} S(t)=\exp\{-\theta F(t)\}, \end{equation*}\] where \(F(t)=\Lambda(t)/\theta\) is a proper cumulative distribution function of a nonnegative random variable with \(F(0)=0\) and \(F(\infty)=\Lambda(\infty)/\theta=1\). As \(t\rightarrow \infty\), one has \(\lim_{t\rightarrow \infty}S(t)=\exp(-\theta)\) which indicates the cure rate. The covariates have a long-term effect because \(\theta\) describes the long-term survival probability. A common choice of \(\theta(\cdot)\) is \(\theta( X)=\exp(\gamma_0+ \gamma^\top X)\). Tsodikov (2002) extends the improper PH model by adding a short-term effect by incorporating covariates into \(F(t)\) or survival function \(\bar{F}(t)=1-F(t)\). The PHPH model of Tsodikov, Ibrahim, and Yakovlev (2003) has the form \[\begin{equation} \label{PHPH} S(t)=\exp[-\theta( X)\{ 1-\bar{F}(t)^{\eta ( Z)} \} ], \end{equation}\] where \(\eta ( Z)=\exp( \phi^\top Z)\) and $ $ is a \(q\)-column vector of regression coefficients. To avoid overparameterization, we assume the coefficients $ $ do not contain an intercept term as suggested in Tsodikov, Ibrahim, and Yakovlev (2003).

MC model: The EM-based approach

The EM-based approach proposed by Peng and Dear (2000) is available in the smcure() function form the R package smcure (Cai et al. 2012). The arguments of smcure() are as follows

> library(smcure)
> packageVersion("smcure")
[1] '2.0'
> args(smcure)
function (formula, cureform, offset = NULL, data, na.action = na.omit, 
    model = c("aft", "ph"), link = "logit", Var = TRUE, emmax = 50, 
    eps = 1e-07, nboot = 100) 
NULL

The main arguments are following (see ?smcure::smcure for a full list).

  • formula a formula object to specify the variables included in the latency component of the MC model
  • cureform a formula object to specify the variables included in the incidence component of the MC model
  • data a data.frame in which to interpret the variables occurring in the formula and cureform
  • model a character string to specify the latency model
  • nboot an integer to specify number of bootstrap sampling

The following fits smcure() to e1684 with covaraites AGE, TRT, and SEX and 100 bootstrap samples.

> smcure(Surv(FAILTIME, FAILCENS) ~ AGE + TRT + SEX, 
+        ~ AGE + TRT + SEX,
+        data = e1684, model = "ph", nboot = 100)

MC model: The proposed pseudo-observation approach

The proposed pseudo-observation approach estimates the regression coefficients in the incidence component and latency component separately.

Incidence component

The mixture cure model has two parameters, uncured rate \(\pi\) and the conditional survival function \(S_u(t)\), to be estimated. The cure rate \(1 - \pi\) can be estimated by \( {\hat{S}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t_{\max})\), where \( {\hat{S}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t)\) is the Kaplan-Meier (KM) estimator (Maller and Zhou 1992). The following is used to obtain \( {\hat{\pi}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}= 1 - {\hat{S}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t_\max)\).

> n <- nrow(e1684)
> tmax <- max(e1684$FAILTIME[e1684$FAILCENS > 0])
> KM <- survfit(Surv(FAILTIME, FAILCENS) ~ 1, data = e1684)
> (cure <- min(KM$surv) )
[1] 0.2830461

The pseudo-observations of \( {\hat{\pi}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}\) for the \(i\)th subject is \[ {\hat{\pi}^{(i)}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}= n\cdot {\hat{\pi}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}- (n - 1)\cdot {\hat{\pi}^{(-i)}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}},\] where \( {\hat{\pi}^{(-i)}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}= 1 - {\hat{S}^{(-i)}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t_\max)\) is the estimator for \(\pi\) without the \(i\)th subject. The following creates a data.frame with the pseudo-observations of \( {\hat{\pi}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}\) stored under curei.

> e1684.inc <- e1684
> e1684.inc$id <- 1:n
> e1684.inc$curei <- n * (1 - cure) - sapply(1:n, function(k) {
+   cure.deletei <- min(update(KM, subset = -k)$surv)
+   (n - 1) * (1 - cure.deletei)
+ })
> head(e1684.inc)
  TRT FAILTIME FAILCENS         AGE SEX TRT.SEX id      curei
1   1  1.15068        1 -11.0359437   0       0  1  1.0025089
2   1  0.62466        1  -5.1290437   0       0  2  1.0025089
3   0  1.89863        0  23.1859563   1       0  3  0.3322519
4   0  0.45479        1  11.1448563   1       0  4  1.0000000
5   0  2.09041        1 -13.3208437   0       0  5  1.0135968
6   1  9.38356        0   0.9421563   0       0  6 -0.4229631

The regression coefficient is estimated via GEE.

> library(geepack)
> fit.inc <- geese(curei ~ AGE + TRT * SEX, data = e1684.inc,
+                 jack = TRUE, scale.fix = TRUE, family = gaussian, mean.link = "logit")
>

> newDat

Latency component

To estimate the regression coefficient in the latency component, we need to create pseudo-observations for \(S_u(t)\). The MC model implies \(S_u(t)\) can be estimated by \[\hat{S}_u(t) = \frac{ {\hat{S}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t) - {\hat{S}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t_\max)}{1 - {\hat{S}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t_\max)}.\] Thus, the pseudo-observation for \(S_u(t)\) can be constructed by \[\begin{equation*} {\hat{S}^{(i)}_u}(t) = n\cdot {\hat{S}_u}(t) - (n - 1)\cdot {\hat{S}^{(-i)}_u}(t), \end{equation*}\] where \[\begin{equation*} {\hat{S}^{(-i)}_u}(t) = \frac{ {\hat{S}^{(-i)}_u}(t) - {\hat{S}^{(-i)}_u}(t_\max)}{1 - {\hat{S}^{(-i)}_u}(t_\max)} \end{equation*}\] is the estimator for \(S_u(t)\) without the \(i\) subject. The following creates a data.frame with the pseudo-observations of \(S_u(t)\) at \(t = \{t_1, \ldots, t_H\}\) stored under variable Si. We consider the pseudo-observation times \(t\) at the \(10, 20, \ldots, 80, 90\), and the 95th percentiles of the observed survival times.

> t0 <- quantile(e1684$FAILTIME[e1684$FAILCENS > 0], c(1:9 / 10, .95))
> S <- KM$surv[findInterval(t0, KM$time)]
> e1684.lat <- e1684[rep(1:n, each = length(t0)),]
> e1684.lat$id <- rep(1:n, each = length(t0))
> e1684.lat$Si <- n * (S - cure) / (1 - cure) - c(sapply(1:n, function(k) { 
+   KM.reduce <- update(KM, subset = -k)
+   S.deletei <- KM.reduce$surv[findInterval(t0, KM.reduce$time)]  
+   cure.deletei <- min(KM.reduce$surv)
+   (n - 1) * (S.deletei - cure.deletei) / (1 - cure.deletei)
+ }))
> e1684.lat$Fi <- 1 - e1684.lat$Si
> e1684.lat$t <- as.factor(rep(t0, n))
> rownames(e1684.lat) <- NULL
> head(e1684.lat)
  TRT FAILTIME FAILCENS       AGE SEX TRT.SEX id       Si          Fi       t
1   1  1.15068        1 -11.03594   0       0  1 1.039315 -0.03931539 0.13014
2   1  1.15068        1 -11.03594   0       0  1 1.080597 -0.08059655 0.19452
3   1  1.15068        1 -11.03594   0       0  1 1.115980 -0.11598040 0.29452

Generalized linear model with a log function, \(\log\{-\log(x)\}\), is used to estimate the regression coefficients in the latency component. However, the complementary log-log link function in standard R approaches, e.g., geese(), corresponds to \(\log\{\log(x)\}\). We thus fit a GEE model with Fi as the response variable.

In general, the implementations of the pseudo-observations construction in the incidence component and latency component can be combined, but we separate those in this example to illustrate the independence of estimating procedures in the two components. We calculate and plot the pseudo residuals (at \(t_2, t_3, t_4\), and \(t_5\)) with the following code.

> e1684.lat$resid <-

> levels(e1684.lat$t) <- paste0("t = ", unique(e1684.lat$t))

The pseudo-residuals fluctuate around zero, indicating the adequacy of the proposed GLM even though the pseudo-residuals have a larger variation in the Control/Male group.

BCH model

As in the MC model, the proposed pseudo-observation approach allows the short-term and long-term covaraites effects in the BCH model to be estimated separately.

Long-term effect

Since the cure rate \(\lim_{t\rightarrow \infty}S(t)=\exp(-\theta)\) can be nonparametrically estimated by \( {\hat{S}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t_{\max})\), \(\theta\) can be estimated by \( {\hat{\theta}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}=-\log {\hat{S}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t_{\max})\). The pseudo-observation of \( {\hat{\theta}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}\) for the \(i\)th subject is \[\begin{equation*} {\hat{\theta}^{(i)}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}= n\cdot {\hat{\theta}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}- (n - 1)\cdot {\hat{\theta}^{(-i)}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}. \end{equation*}\] The following codes create a data.frame with the pseudo-observation for \( {\hat{\theta}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}\) stored under thetai.

> e1684.long <- e1684
> e1684.long$id <- 1:n
> e1684.long$thetai <- n * (-log(cure)) - sapply(1:n, function(k) {
+   cure.deletei <- min(update(KM, subset = -k)$surv)
+   (n - 1) * (-log(cure.deletei))
+ })
> head(e1684.long)
  TRT FAILTIME FAILCENS         AGE SEX TRT.SEX id     thetai
1   1  1.15068        1 -11.0359437   0       0  1  2.2692153
2   1  0.62466        1  -5.1290437   0       0  2  2.2692153
3   0  1.89863        0  23.1859563   1       0  3 -0.1002781
4   0  0.45479        1  11.1448563   1       0  4  2.2603828
5   0  2.09041        1 -13.3208437   0       0  5  2.3082471
6   1  9.38356        0   0.9421563   0       0  6 -2.7941042

The regression coefficient is estimated via GEE.

Short-term effect

Based Tsodikov (2002), \(F(t)\) can be consistently estimated by \( {\hat{F}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t)=\log( {\hat{S}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t))/\log( {\hat{S}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t_{\max}))\). Thus, the pseudo-observations for \(F(t)\) can be created by \[\begin{equation*} {\hat{F}^{(i)}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t)=n\cdot {\hat{F}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t)-(n-1)\cdot {\hat{F}^{(-i)}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t), \end{equation*}\] where \( {\hat{F}^{(-i)}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t)\) is the estimate of \( {\hat{F}_{\scriptsize\text{KM}}}(t)\) without the \(i\)th subject.

The following creates a data.frame with the pseudo-observations of \(F(u)\) stored under variable Fi. We consider the pseudo-observation times \(t\) at the \(10,20, \ldots, 80,90\), and the 95th percentiles of the observed survival times.

> e1684.short <- e1684[rep(1:n, each = length(t0)),]
> e1684.short$id <- rep(1:n, each = length(t0))
> e1684.short$Fi <- n * (log(S) / log(cure)) - c(sapply(1:n, function(k) {
+   KM.reduce <- update(KM, subset = -k)
+   S.deletei <- KM.reduce$surv[findInterval(t0, KM.reduce$time)]  
+   cure.deletei <- min(KM.reduce$surv)
+   (n - 1) * log(S.deletei) / log(cure.deletei) 
+ }))
> e1684.short$t <- as.factor(rep(t0, n))
> rownames(e1684.short) <- NULL
> head(e1684.short)

Generalized linear model with a log function, \(\log\{−\log(x)\}\), is used to estimate the regression coefficients in the latency component.

> fit.short <- geese(Fi ~ 0 + t + AGE + TRT * SEX, data = e1684.short,
+              jack = TRUE, scale.fix = TRUE, family = gaussian, mean.link = "cloglog")

We calculate and plot the pseudo residuals (at \(t_2, t_3, t_4\), and \(t_5\)) with the following code.

> e1684.short$resid <- 1 - e1684.short$Fi - exp(-exp(
+   model.matrix(~ 0 + t + AGE + TRT * SEX, e1684.short) %*% fit.short$beta))
> levels(e1684.short$t) <- paste0("t = ", unique(e1684.short$t))
> ggplot(subset(e1684.short, t0 %in% t0[2:5 * 2]), 
+        aes(x = interaction(TRT, SEX), y = resid, fill = interaction(TRT, SEX))) +
+   facet_wrap(~ t) + geom_boxplot() + ylab("Residual") +
+   scale_fill_discrete(labels = c("Control/Male", "Control/Female",
